  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n3. Expansion of Regulatory Framework\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased information sharing between financial institutions\n- Stricter customer identification procedures\n\n4. Global Compliance Measures\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Mandatory risk assessments\n- Transaction monitoring systems\n\n5. Recent Developments\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced digital transaction tracking\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Broader definition of financial institutions\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- Advanced AI and machine learning algorithms\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Automated suspicious activity detection\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, addressing emerging financial technologies and global economic challenges.",
